As our energy system must urgently transition to a larger dependence on solar energy, I thought it could be worthwhile to walk through the physical limits imposed by the terrestrial solar spectrum.

We start with the reference solar spectrum ASTM G173-03, as defined by ASTM and published by NREL, which is included as ASTMG173 in this package:

dataset <- photoec::ASTMG173
dataset %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 2,002
## Columns: 4
## $ wavelength         <dbl> 280.0, 280.5, 281.0, 281.5, 282.0, 282.5, 283.0, 283.5,…
## $ extraterrestrial   <dbl> 0.08200, 0.09900, 0.15000, 0.21200, 0.26700, 0.30300, 0…
## $ globaltilt         <dbl> 4.7309e-23, 1.2307e-21, 5.6895e-21, 1.5662e-19, 1.1946e…
## $ direct.circumsolar <dbl> 2.5361e-26, 1.0917e-24, 6.1253e-24, 2.7479e-22, 2.8346e…

This dataframe is in wide format. To make plotting (with ggplot2) faster, let’s transform it to long format.

# while we are at it, let's give the existing columns more descriptive names
dataset <- dataset %>%
   rename(AM0 = extraterrestrial) %>%
   rename(AM1.5G = globaltilt) %>%
   # direct normal circumsolar
   rename(DNCS = direct.circumsolar)
datalong <- dataset %>% pivot_longer(
   cols = !starts_with("wavelength"),
   names_to = "model",
   values_to = "value") %>%
   mutate(property = "spectralirradiance")
datalong %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 6,006
## Columns: 4
## $ wavelength <dbl> 280.0, 280.0, 280.0, 280.5, 280.5, 280.5, 281.0, 281.0, 281.0, …
## $ model      <chr> "AM0", "AM1.5G", "DNCS", "AM0", "AM1.5G", "DNCS", "AM0", "AM1.5…
## $ value      <dbl> 8.2000e-02, 4.7309e-23, 2.5361e-26, 9.9000e-02, 1.2307e-21, 1.0…
## $ property   <chr> "spectralirradiance", "spectralirradiance", "spectralirradiance…

Now, as a sanity check, let’s compare the spectra returned by this package’s sunlight.ASTM() function with those above (should be an exact match).

They look the same, and indeed, the values (here exemplified by AM1.5G) returned by the dataset and the function are pairwise equal, as expected:

dplyr::near(
   datalong %>% filter(model == "AM1.5G") %>% filter(property == "spectralirradiance") %>% pull(value),
   dflong %>% filter(model == "AM1.5G") %>% filter(property == "spectralirradiance") %>% pull(value)) %>% all()
## [1] TRUE

Whereas the dataset contains only spectral irradiance, the dataframe returned by this package’s sunlight.ASTM() function derives other properties, namely, absolute and relative cumulative irradiance (irradiance and irradiance.fraction), spectral photon flux (spectralphotonflux) and absolute and relative cumulative photon flux (photonflux and photonflux.fraction).

Quick reminder: AM0 is the extra-terrestrial irradiance (solar spectrum just outside earth’s atmosphere), and AM1.5G is the solar spectrum at sea-level at mid-latitudes, and DNCS is the direct normal circumsolar spectrum which excludes diffuse light. In the following we will discuss only AM1.5G, unless otherwise noted. About 75% of the total irradiance (i.e., power) is contained below 1000 nm, but only about 50% of the total photon flux. This makes sense, since each lower-wavelength photon carries more energy.

Please note that the spectral irradiance and flux shown in the table are not summed over the wavelength step. That is, they are simply the value at the shown wavelength, and not the spectral irradiance/flux summed over the wavelength step (10 nm in this case). The calculated current density and STH values assume perfect quantum efficiency, Faradaic efficiency and no band gap and are only meant as an illustrative ceiling.
